#VASCULAR: The exam is of suboptimal quality for diagnosis of pulmonary embolism secondary to patient habitus.
#There are no secondary findings of  peripheral occlusive pulmonary embolism
#Findings are consistent with intermediate probability for pulmonary  embolism.
#Indications: Pulmonary embolism seen on prior study.
#No secondary manifestations of  peripheral occlusive pulmonary embolism including acute vessel caliber change or pleural-based lung opacity.
#Scintigraphic findings are consistent with a low probability for pulmonary embolism.
#4) and image 40 of series 7) which could represent small old/chronic pulmonary embolism.
#VASCULAR: The bolus is of poor quality for diagnosis of pulmonary embolism.
#STUDY QUALITY: The examination is suboptimal for the diagnosis of pulmonary embolism.
#STUDY QUALITY: The examination is adequate for the diagnosis of pulmonary embolism.
#EXAM: CT chest with contrast pulmonary arteries for pulmonary embolism
#INDICATION: Chest pain, prior pulmonary embolus x2, factor V Leiden
#Virtually excludes possibility of acute pulmonary embolism..
#However, most perfusions abnormalities would be expected to resolve by 8 weeks following a PE. Therefore, a prior PE cannot be excluded.
#Views of the femoral vein in the distal thigh and the tibial veins in most of the left calf are compromised due to restricted patient positioning and  pain.
#Small residual filling defects in a branch to right upper lobe and right lower lobe posterior basal branch where previous pulmonary emboli were seen and could represent chronic emboli at this time.
#There is a filling defect spanning the bifurcation of the pulmonary trunk consistent with a nonocclusive saddle embolus.
#...consistent with low likelihood ratio of pulmonary embolism.
#Depending on the overall level of suspicion for pulmonary embolism, further evaluation may be performed
#Focal pulmonary hemorrhage from pulmonary embolism may produce such an opacity.
